Overdetermined Linear System of Equations¶

Consider the following system of mm linear equations in nn variables. a11x1+a12x2+⋯+a1nxn=b1a21x1+a22x2+⋯+a2nxn=b2⋮ am1x1+am2x2+⋯+amnxn=bm,a11x1+a12x2+⋯+a1nxn=b1a21x1+a22x2+⋯+a2nxn=b2⋮ am1x1+am2x2+⋯+amnxn=bm,

  • The system could be represented in a compact form as Ax=bAx=b, where A=⎛⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜⎝a11a12⋯a1na21a22⋯a2n⋮⋮⋱⋮am1am2⋯amn⎞⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟⎠,x=⎛⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜⎝x1x2⋮xn⎞⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟⎠,b=⎛⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜⎝b1b2⋮bm⎞⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟⎠A=(a11a12⋯a1na21a22⋯a2n⋮⋮⋱⋮am1am2⋯amn),x=(x1x2⋮xn),b=(b1b2⋮bm)

  • The solution of a linear system represents the point of intersection of hyperplanes given by the lienar equations.

  • The solution also represents the linear coding of the columns of a matrix AA to get a vector bb in the column space (C(A)C(A)).
x1⎛⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜⎝a11a21⋮am1⎞⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟⎠+x2⎛⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜⎝a12a22⋮am2⎞⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟⎠+⋯+xn⎛⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜⎝a1na2n⋮amn⎞⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟⎠=⎛⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜⎝b1b2⋮bm⎞⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟⎠x1(a11a21⋮am1)+x2(a12a22⋮am2)+⋯+xn(a1na2n⋮amn)=(b1b2⋮bm)

or simply as x1A:1+x2A:2+⋯+xnA:n=bx1A:1+x2A:2+⋯+xnA:n=b

  • The system is called...

    • a square system when m=nm=n. Admits a unique solution only when AA is invertible.

    • an overdetermined when m>nm>n.

    • an underdetermined when m<nm<n.

B. No over-determined system has any solution.

Least Square Problems (LSP)¶

When m>nm>n the number of variables is less than the number of equations. These systems are rarely exactly solvable. However, in an approximate sense, we would like to find a vector AxAx in the column space of AA which is closest to bb. In such a case, we aim to find xx such that the residual vector r=b−Axr=b−Ax as small as possible.

LSP Formulation For A∈Rm×nA∈Rm×n (where m≥nm≥n) and b∈Rmb∈Rm, find the vector x∈Rnx∈Rn that minimize minimizex∈Rn∥Ax−b∥22minimizex∈Rn‖Ax−b‖22
🤔 Why should we use l2l2 norm and not some other norms such as l1l1 or l∞l∞ norm?
The function is differentiable in l2l2 norm. Moreover, orthogonal transformations could be used as l2l2 norms are invariant under multiplication of the vectors by orthogonal matrices. This leads to better numerical solutions.

Please note the equivalent formulation of the minimizer as

^x=argminx∈Rn(b−Ax)T(b−Ax)x^=argminx∈Rn(b−Ax)T(b−Ax)

⛳ Note that from our discussion on matrix calculus and optimization, the gradient of the above function was found to be AT(Ax−b)AT(Ax−b) which also leads to the normal equations discussed ahead.

Theorem

The vector x∈Rnx∈Rn minimizes the residual norm, ∥r∥=∥b−Ax∥2‖r‖=‖b−Ax‖2, if and only if r⊥col(A)r⊥col(A).

It follows from the above theorem that r⊥col(A)⟹r∈N(AT)r⊥col(A)⟹r∈N(AT) as column space and left-null space are orthogonal.( Recall C(A)⊕N(AT)=RmC(A)⊕N(AT)=Rm. ) This implies that ATr=0AT(b−Ax)=0ATAx=ATbATr=0AT(b−Ax)=0ATAx=ATb

Which naturally leads us to the normal equations ATAx=ATb.ATAx=ATb. Note, the computation above attempts to demonstrate how the normal equations solve the LSP problem by minimizing the residual norm.

Discussion The condition number while solving the normal equations.

The condition number of rectangular matrix BB of rank rr could be given by κ(B)=σ1(B)σr(B)κ(B)=σ1(B)σr(B)

The condition number for the systems of normal eqaution thus comes out to be κ(ATA)=σ21σ2r=[κ(A)]2κ(ATA)=σ12σr2=[κ(A)]2

❗ High condition number for AA suggest trouble in the case of nearly rank-deficient problems.

Theorem

For A∈Rm×nA∈Rm×n (where m≥nm≥n) and b∈Rmb∈Rm, if the vector x∈Rnx∈Rn satisfies the condition ATAx=ATbATAx=ATb, then xx solves the least square problem.

Example: Solve the following system in the least square sense

3x+2y=32x+3y=0x+2y=1(1)(2)(3)(1)3x+2y=3(2)2x+3y=0(3)x+2y=1

Or, in matrix-vector form ⎛⎜⎝322312⎞⎟⎠A(xy)x=⎛⎜⎝301⎞⎟⎠b(322312)⏟A(xy)⏟x=(301)⏟b We have the normal equations ATAx=ATbATAx=ATb (14141417)x=(108)(14141417)x=(108)

By using Gaussian elimination, we have ⎛⎝1414⋮101417⋮8⎞⎠⟶⎛⎝1414⋮1003⋮−2⎞⎠(1414⋮101417⋮8)⟶(1414⋮1003⋮−2) The last row from above gives 3x2=−2⇒x2=−233x2=−2⇒x2=−23.

From the first row we get x1=(10−14(−2/3))/14=2921x1=(10−14(−2/3))/14=2921.

Connection with Projection¶

When the solution of the LSP (in full column rank case) is ^x=(ATA)−1ATbx^=(ATA)−1ATb, the projection of vector bb onto the column space of AA is A^x=A(ATA)−1ATbAx^=A(ATA)−1ATb. So, the projection matrix that projects vector bb onto the column space of AA is given by ^H=A(ATA)−1AT,H^=A(ATA)−1AT, and the residual, ^r=b−A^x=(I−^H)br^=b−Ax^=(I−H^)b.

Full Rank LSP Solutions¶

When AA is full column rank, the matrix ATAATA is invertible and the normal equations coudl be solve simply (or naively) by ATAx=ATb⟺x=(ATA)−1ATbATAx=ATb⟺x=(ATA)−1ATb

Solving LSP by using Cholesky Decomposition¶

It follows that ATAATA is a symmetric positive semi-definite matrix. Therefore, once our normal matrix has been constructed, we can apply Cholesky decomposition to further simplify our least square problem. In fact, the use of Cholesky decomposition allows the original problem to be stated in a way that is efficiently solved by numerical solutions.

Theorem: Cholesky Decomposition For any real positive-definite matrix B∈Rn×nB∈Rn×n, there exists a qnique lower triangular matrix L∈Rn×nL∈Rn×n so that BB is decomposed as B=LLTB=LLT.

In LSP, if the matric AA is full column-rank, ATAATA is symmetric positive defintie and satisfies the conditions for Cholesky decomposition ATA=LLTATA=LLT. It follows that ATAx=ATb⟹LLTx=ATbATAx=ATb⟹LLTx=ATb

By letting LTx=zLTx=z, we can solve the following system by forward substitution Lz=ATbLz=ATb

Once we have solved for zz, we can finally solve for xx by backward substitution LTx=zLTx=z

Note: The order of floating point operations is O(13n3+mn2)≈mn2+13n3flopsO(13n3+mn2)≈mn2+13n3flops


Solving LSP using QR Decomposition¶

Theorem: QR Decomposition

For any matrix A∈Rm×nA∈Rm×n, there exists an orthogonal matrix Q∈Rm×mQ∈Rm×m and an upper triangular matrix R∈Rm×nR∈Rm×n so that AA is decomposed as A=QRA=QR.

Thin (Economy) QR For any matrix A∈Rm×nA∈Rm×n, A=Q1R1A=Q1R1 where matrix Q1∈Rm×nQ1∈Rm×n is an orthonormal column matrix and R1∈Rn×nR1∈Rn×n is an upper triangular matrix.

Images Source

Recall our original goal for least square problems minimizex∈Rn∥Ax−b∥22minimizex∈Rn‖Ax−b‖22

If we apply QR decomposition to AA, we observe: ∥Ax−b∥22=∥QRx−b∥22‖Ax−b‖22=‖QRx−b‖22

Since QQ is orthogonal, we can multiply by QTQT and the 2-norm will remain unchanged. =∥QT(QRx−b)∥22=∥QTQRx−QTb∥22=‖QT(QRx−b)‖22=‖QTQRx−QTb‖22

Which can be simplifed by using the thin-QR decomposition as follows

∥Rx−QTb∥22=∥∥ ∥∥[R10]x−[QT1QT2]b∥∥ ∥∥22=∥∥ ∥∥[R1x−QT1b0−QT2b]∥∥ ∥∥22=∥R1x−QT1b∥22+∥QT2b∥22‖Rx−QTb‖22=‖[R10]x−[Q1TQ2T]b‖22=‖[R1x−Q1Tb0−Q2Tb]‖22=‖R1x−Q1Tb‖22+‖Q2Tb‖22


Finally, the expression on the right could be minimized by having R1x−QT1b=0R1x−Q1Tb=0. Since R1R1 is upper triangular, we can solve for xx by back-substitution R1x=QT1bR1x=Q1Tb.

The order of floating point operations in this procedure is

2mn2−23n3flops2mn2−23n3flops

Connection with Projection¶

When the solution of the LSP (in full column rank case) is ^x=(ATA)−1ATbx^=(ATA)−1ATb, the projection of vector bb onto the column space of AA is A^x=A(ATA)−1ATbAx^=A(ATA)−1ATb. So, the projection matrix that projects vector bb onto the column space of AA is given by ^H=A(ATA)−1AT,H^=A(ATA)−1AT, and the residual, ^r=b−A^x=(I−^H)br^=b−Ax^=(I−H^)b.

Solving LSP by using SVD¶

In the case of a full column-rank matrix AA, the economy SVD could be given by A=U(n)Σ(n)VTA=U(n)Σ(n)VT, where U(n)U(n) is made of the first nn columns of UU (from full SVD). Please note that the dimensions of these matrices are m×nm×n, n×nn×n and n×nn×n respectively.

The projection matrix that projects AA onto the column space of AA could be given by P=U(n)UT(n)P=U(n)U(n)T as the columns of U(n)U(n) provide an orthonormal basis for the column space of AA. There for xx is such that Ax=PbAx=Pb. This implies
U(n)Σ(n)VTx=U(n)UT(n)b⟺UT(n)U(n)Σ(n)VTx=UT(n)U(n)UT(n)bU(n)Σ(n)VTx=U(n)U(n)Tb⟺U(n)TU(n)Σ(n)VTx=U(n)TU(n)U(n)Tb
It should be noted that UT(n)U(n)=InU(n)TU(n)=In, so we have the equivalent system

Σ(n)VTx=UT(n)b⟹x=VΣ−1(n)UT(n)bΣ(n)VTx=U(n)Tb⟹x=VΣ(n)−1U(n)Tb


The number of floating point operations in this approach is ≈2mn2+11n3flops≈2mn2+11n3flops

SVD and Rank-deficient (multi-collinear) LSP¶

When the matrix AA in the LSP is not full-rank, the normal equations have infinitely many solutions. Let χχ be the set of all such solutions χ={x∈Rn:ATAx=ATb}χ={x∈Rn:ATAx=ATb}

🤔 Can you prove that the set of all such least square solution is a convex set?

Our aim is to find the unique LSP solution that has the smallest l2l2 norm. We will denote it by xLSxLS. SVD provides the approach to find such a solution.

Theorem Let the SVD of rank rr matrix A∈Rm×nA∈Rm×n, be given by A=r∑i=1σiUiVTi,A=∑i=1rσiUiViT, in the outer product form, then the `smallest' least square solution to the LSP is given by xLS=r∑i=1(UTibσi)VixLS=∑i=1r(UiTbσi)Vi and the minimum residual norm is obtained by ρ2LS=m∑i=r+1(UTib)2.ρLS2=∑i=r+1m(UiTb)2.

The proof of the above follows from the fact that
∥Ax−b∥22=∥UΣVTx−b∥22=∥ΣVTx−UTb∥22=∥Σz−UTb∥22‖Ax−b‖22=‖UΣVTx−b‖22=‖ΣVTx−UTb‖22=‖Σz−UTb‖22
where z=VTxz=VTx. Then the expression on the right could be expressed as
∥∥ ∥ ∥ ∥ ∥ ∥ ∥ ∥ ∥∥ ⎛⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜⎝σ1z1⋮σrzr0⋮0⎞⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟⎠−⎛⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜⎝UT1b⋮UTrbUTr+1b⋮UTmb⎞⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟⎠ ∥∥ ∥ ∥ ∥ ∥ ∥ ∥ ∥ ∥∥22=∥∥ ∥ ∥ ∥ ∥ ∥ ∥ ∥ ∥∥ ⎛⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜ ⎜⎝σ1z1−UT1b⋮σrzr−UTrb−UTr+1b⋮−UTmb⎞⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟ ⎟⎠ ∥∥ ∥ ∥ ∥ ∥ ∥ ∥ ∥ ∥∥22=r∑i=1(σizi−UTib)2+m∑i=r+1(UTib)2‖ (σ1z1⋮σrzr0⋮0)−(U1Tb⋮UrTbUr+1Tb⋮UmTb) ‖22=‖ (σ1z1−U1Tb⋮σrzr−UrTb−Ur+1Tb⋮−UmTb) ‖22=∑i=1r(σizi−UiTb)2+∑i=r+1m(UiTb)2
Clearly, the above expression will admit the minimum value ∑mi=r+1(UTib)2∑i=r+1m(UiTb)2 only when the first expression is zero, implying that zi=UTib/σizi=UiTb/σi for i=1:ri=1:r. In addition, the smallest ∥x∥2‖x‖2 norm will require zi=0zi=0 for i=r+1:ni=r+1:n. Therefore,
x=Vz=r∑i=1ziVi=r∑i=1(UTibσi)Vix=Vz=∑i=1rziVi=∑i=1r(UiTbσi)Vi

Pseudoinverse and LSP¶

We defined pseudo-inverse when we studied SVD. Here is the definition again for all to recall.

Pseudo-inverse (Moore-Penrose Inverse)¶

The pseudo-inverse of a rectangular matrix A∈Rm×nA∈Rm×n of rank rr, whose SVD is given by A=UΣVTA=UΣVT, is a unique rectangular matrix A+∈Rn×mA+∈Rn×m, given by

A+=VΣ+UTA+=VΣ+UT

where Σ+=diag(1σ1, 1σ2, ⋯, 1σr, 0, ⋯, 0)∈Rn×mΣ+=diag(1σ1, 1σ2, ⋯, 1σr, 0, ⋯, 0)∈Rn×m

It turns out from above that the calculation of smallest least square solution in the case of rank-deficient LSP could actaully be performed by the pseudo-inverse as
xLS=A+bandρLS=∥b−AxLS∥2=∥b−AA+b∥2=∥(I−AA+)b∥2xLS=A+bandρLS=‖b−AxLS‖2=‖b−AA+b‖2=‖(I−AA+)b‖2

We have at different occassions proved several properties of pseudo-inverse. Here are some of them

  • When m=n=rank(A)m=n=rank(A), the pseudoinverse is the inverse: A+=A−1A+=A−1.

  • When AA is full row-rank, m=rank(A)m=rank(A) and A+=AT(AAT)−1A+=AT(AAT)−1 is the right inverse of AA.

  • When AA is full column-rank, n=rank(A)n=rank(A), A+=(ATA)−1ATA+=(ATA)−1AT is the left inverse of AA.

  • The matrix P=AA+P=AA+ is an orthogonal projection onto column space C(A)C(A).

  • The matrix P=A+AP=A+A is an orthogonal projection onto row space R(A)R(A).

Here is a problem that you should be able to solve by using the ideas from matrix calculus and optimization.

🤔 The pseudoinverse is the unique minimal solution to the problem minimizeX∈Rn×m∥AX−I∥F.minimizeX∈Rn×m‖AX−I‖F.

Variants for LSP¶

Weighted Least Square Problems

^x=argminx∈Rn(b−Ax)TW(b−Ax)x^=argminx∈Rn(b−Ax)TW(b−Ax)

where WW is a diagonal matrix of non-negative weights that assigns weights to different observations in the least square formulation.

Generalized Least Square Problems

^x=argminx∈Rn(b−Ax)TΩ−1(b−Ax)x^=argminx∈Rn(b−Ax)TΩ−1(b−Ax)

where ΩΩ is the covariance matrix for the data.


🤔 Can you show that the formulation of the generalized LSP is equivalent to the follwing constrained problem. minimize vTvsubject to b=Ax+Ω1/2vminimize vTvsubject to b=Ax+Ω1/2v

Column-weighted Least Square Problems If we scale the columns of the matrix AA then the LSP computes the solution of minimizez∈Rn∥(AG−1)z−b∥22minimizez∈Rn‖(AG−1)z−b‖22


Such scaling is common place, for example, in normalization of features of a data-matrix such as G=G2:=diag{∥A1∥2,∥A2∥2,⋯,∥An∥2}G=G2:=diag{‖A1‖2,‖A2‖2,⋯,‖An‖2} It has been shown that with this choice of the scaling, the condition number κ(AG−1)κ(AG−1) is approximately minimized that affects the accuracy of zLSzLS. However, some orthogonalization based methods may not return the same estimate (see p.307 Golub).

Regularized LSP¶

In ridge regression, we solve an optimization problem in the following form minimizex∈Rn∥Ax−b∥22+λ∥x∥22minimizex∈Rn‖Ax−b‖22+λ‖x‖22 where the ridge-penalty λλ is chosen to shape the solution in some desired way.

🤔 Can you show that the normal equations for this problem is given by (ATA+λI)x=ATb(ATA+λI)x=ATb

One clear advantage of using this regularization is that it takes care of the near rank-deficiency (multicolliniarity) of AA as ATA+λIATA+λI could be made invertible by choosing λλ appropriately. See Golub (p 307-308) on how λλ could be chosen in an optimum way.


🤔 Follow the SVD of A=UΣVTA=UΣVT method discussed earlier to show that (ΣTΣ+λI)VTx=ΣTUTb(ΣTΣ+λI)VTx=ΣTUTb and hence x(λ)=r∑i=1σiUTibσ2i+λVix(λ)=∑i=1rσiUiTbσi2+λVi

In Tikhonov regularization problem, we solve an optimization problem in the form minimizex∈Rn∥Ax−b∥22+λ∥Bx∥22minimizex∈Rn‖Ax−b‖22+λ‖Bx‖22 where B∈Rn×nB∈Rn×n.

🤔 Can you show that the normal equations for this problem is given by (ATA+λBTB)x=ATb.(ATA+λBTB)x=ATb.
